than good food, you'll look another way.

521
00:26:34,780 --> 00:26:38,860
So the value rankings are as important or more important

522
00:26:38,860 --> 00:26:41,140
than the actual values themselves.

523
00:26:41,140 --> 00:26:42,740
Culture is always shifting.

524
00:26:42,740 --> 00:26:50,380
So universal grammar is a very popular term.

525
00:26:50,380 --> 00:26:53,740
It was made popular in modern times by Noam Chomsky.

526
00:26:53,740 --> 00:26:56,660
Although the term goes back to the 12th century,

527
00:26:56,660 --> 00:26:58,580
grammarians known as the modesty.

528
00:26:58,580 --> 00:27:01,820
And in the US, the first person to ever talk about universal

529
00:27:01,820 --> 00:27:05,380
grammar was Charles Sanders Purse.

530
00:27:05,380 --> 00:27:10,780
His view of grammar was both he and Chomsky, interestingly

531
00:27:10,780 --> 00:27:15,020
enough, felt that recursion, I can

532
00:27:15,020 --> 00:27:16,780
talk about recursion separately, but anyway, they thought

533
00:27:16,780 --> 00:27:20,020
that recursion was the basis of grammar.

534
00:27:20,020 --> 00:27:24,060
But for Purse, it was meaning, recursive meanings, not forms,

535
00:27:24,060 --> 00:27:25,140
not the sentences.

536
00:27:25,140 --> 00:27:28,660
But the way that, so for example, if I say bachelor,

537
00:27:28,660 --> 00:27:33,100
I have to interpret that in terms of, say, unmarried man.

538
00:27:33,100 --> 00:27:35,780
And I interpret unmarried in terms of other symbols.

539
00:27:35,780 --> 00:27:38,260
And I interpret man in terms of other symbols

540
00:27:38,260 --> 00:27:42,020
so that every symbol starts us to a recursive chain that

541
00:27:42,020 --> 00:27:44,340
has no end.

542
00:27:44,340 --> 00:27:45,380
Everything is connected.

543
00:27:45,380 --> 00:27:47,940
And to understand one thing, we have to understand a great

544
00:27:47,940 --> 00:27:48,980
deal of culture.

545
00:27:51,420 --> 00:27:56,060
So the difference is for Purse universal grammar followed

546
00:27:56,060 --> 00:27:58,180
from logical principles.

547
00:27:58,180 --> 00:28:01,660
There was nothing necessarily genetic about it.

548
00:28:01,660 --> 00:28:03,740
It simply followed from logical principles.

549
00:28:03,740 --> 00:28:06,620
If you had symbols, they were subject to certain logical

550
00:28:06,620 --> 00:28:09,140
constraints, and those would affect the form of the

551
00:28:09,140 --> 00:28:11,540
language.

552
00:28:11,540 --> 00:28:15,060
Whereas the second version of universal grammar, Chomsky's

553
00:28:15,060 --> 00:28:20,220
is that not only is human biology responsible for

554
00:28:20,220 --> 00:28:24,620
underwriting human linguistic capacity, but the genes are,

555
00:28:24,620 --> 00:28:26,580
there are specific genes linked to language.

556
00:28:29,260 --> 00:28:32,860
So those are very different views of universal grammar.

557
00:28:32,860 --> 00:28:35,260
So now let's move on to tools.

558
00:28:35,300 --> 00:28:38,260
Tools turn out to be a very important part of reasoning

559
00:28:38,260 --> 00:28:41,460
about the origins of human language.

560
00:28:41,460 --> 00:28:45,420
Tools are individual devices or processes that meet perceived

561
00:28:45,420 --> 00:28:48,900
needs of individuals and communities, or a set of

562
00:28:48,900 --> 00:28:51,780
devices, processes, and expertise used to harness the

563
00:28:51,780 --> 00:28:54,460
properties of a particular material.

564
00:28:54,460 --> 00:28:57,540
Full culturally constructed repertoire of knowledge,

565
00:28:57,540 --> 00:28:59,940
conventions, devices, and processes.

566
00:28:59,940 --> 00:29:01,900
Values are vital at each stage.

567
00:29:01,900 --> 00:29:04,540
So tools are really complicated.

568
00:29:04,540 --> 00:29:06,740
This is clearly a complicated tool.

569
00:29:06,740 --> 00:29:07,980
But so is a shovel.

570
00:29:07,980 --> 00:29:13,980
A shovel has a specific kind of function, and if you make a

571
00:29:13,980 --> 00:29:17,820
shovel out of rubber, it won't work very well.

572
00:29:17,820 --> 00:29:21,300
So there's a whole lot of things that have to go into a tool

573
00:29:21,300 --> 00:29:25,340
as simple as a shovel or a knife to make it be what it is.

574
00:29:25,340 --> 00:29:29,100
And it starts to take on meaning features that go

575
00:29:29,100 --> 00:29:31,060
beyond its function.

576
00:29:31,100 --> 00:29:34,820
Human technology enmeshes the material with the ideational.

577
00:29:34,820 --> 00:29:40,540
We have ideas, and they're manifested materially.

578
00:29:40,540 --> 00:29:43,900
Tools involve social constructivism.

579
00:29:43,900 --> 00:29:46,900
Tools become symbols as they emerge from the values,

580
00:29:46,900 --> 00:29:49,060
knowledge, structures, and social roles of a particular

581
00:29:49,060 --> 00:29:50,140
culture.

582
00:29:50,140 --> 00:29:53,380
Symbolism in erectus tools is therefore crucial evidence.

583
00:29:53,380 --> 00:29:56,620
So that's one thing we really need to look for in addition

584
00:29:56,620 --> 00:29:59,300
to the other accomplishments of erectus.

585
00:29:59,300 --> 00:30:02,540
Now, it's true that other species have tools.

586
00:30:02,540 --> 00:30:07,460
But other species' tools tend to be opportunistic.

587
00:30:07,460 --> 00:30:09,500
And one of the interesting things, for example, about

588
00:30:09,500 --> 00:30:12,060
erectus is that they took very good care of their tools.

589
00:30:12,060 --> 00:30:13,020
They colored their tools.

590
00:30:13,020 --> 00:30:15,660
They carried their tools with them over long distances.

591
00:30:15,660 --> 00:30:17,500
They planned ahead.

592
00:30:17,500 --> 00:30:20,420
No other species is known to do that.

593
00:30:20,420 --> 00:30:23,620
Although it's a good Darwinian, I wouldn't want to say that

594
00:30:23,620 --> 00:30:25,740
no other species could, you know, I wouldn't want to

595
00:30:25,740 --> 00:30:27,300
predict what no other species could do.

596
00:30:27,300 --> 00:30:29,540
Because every time somebody tries to do that, we find

597
00:30:29,540 --> 00:30:31,820
that they can.

598
00:30:31,820 --> 00:30:34,140
Learning of technical skills takes place using a

599
00:30:34,140 --> 00:30:36,660
combination of language, gesture, imitation, and

600
00:30:36,660 --> 00:30:37,660
guided intervention.

601
00:30:37,660 --> 00:30:40,220
This applies to all erectus, neanderthal, ensus, and

602
00:30:40,220 --> 00:30:41,500
sapiens tools.

603
00:30:41,500 --> 00:30:44,100
And we'll be getting to that.

604
00:30:44,100 --> 00:30:46,980
This is partially based on lab experiments with stone tool

605
00:30:46,980 --> 00:30:47,540
users.

606
00:30:47,540 --> 00:30:51,020
And my experience in the Amazon, I see this too.

607
00:30:51,020 --> 00:30:55,420
So at the many archaeology departments, they have

608
00:30:55,420 --> 00:31:01,740
napping labs, K, N, A, P, P, not N, A, P. And they learn to

609
00:31:01,740 --> 00:31:02,420
make stone tools.

610
00:31:02,420 --> 00:31:04,020
Graduate students learn to make stone tools.

611
00:31:04,020 --> 00:31:05,540
And they bruise their hands.

612
00:31:05,540 --> 00:31:06,340
They cut their hands.

613
00:31:06,340 --> 00:31:07,700
It's really hard.

614
00:31:07,700 --> 00:31:10,420
So the simplest form of stone tool is like the older one

615
00:31:10,420 --> 00:31:13,260
tools, which we'll see a picture of.

616
00:31:13,260 --> 00:31:15,900
Those take a couple of hundred hours very often for

617
00:31:15,900 --> 00:31:19,780
students, PhD students, to learn to make accurately.

618
00:31:19,780 --> 00:31:23,980
When we get into the more complex tools, it takes a

619
00:31:23,980 --> 00:31:24,740
lot longer.

620
00:31:24,740 --> 00:31:28,060
And what people have found in these labs is that even the

621
00:31:28,060 --> 00:31:32,100
simplest tools, it's very hard to simply show by example how

622
00:31:32,100 --> 00:31:32,940
to do it.

623
00:31:32,940 --> 00:31:38,580
Language tends to be implicated in this skill

624
00:31:38,580 --> 00:31:39,220
acquisition.

625
00:31:39,220 --> 00:31:41,380
Now, this could simply be because they're sapiens, right?

626
00:31:41,380 --> 00:31:42,180
And sapiens talk.

627
00:31:42,180 --> 00:31:45,860
So why not avail yourself of the speech that you have?

628
00:31:45,860 --> 00:31:51,500
In the Amazon, I have watched many men teach their sons

629
00:31:51,540 --> 00:31:55,180
how to make tools like blowguns and bows and arrows.

630
00:31:55,180 --> 00:31:57,940
And a lot of the time is in silence.

631
00:31:57,940 --> 00:32:01,340
But then you'll often hear a question and an answer about

632
00:32:01,340 --> 00:32:04,140
something that was very difficult to see or a movement

633
00:32:04,140 --> 00:32:06,020
that was very quick.

634
00:32:06,020 --> 00:32:12,060
So tools take explanation in many cases.

635
00:32:12,060 --> 00:32:15,860
So once again, on a sign, a sign refers to an object.

636
00:32:16,260 --> 00:32:21,580
So if I have a sign, if I say water, that's the object.

637
00:32:21,580 --> 00:32:24,540
And the representation is W-A-T-E-R.

638
00:32:24,540 --> 00:32:26,700
And the interpretation that you're going to make is

639
00:32:26,700 --> 00:32:29,700
something to drink.

640
00:32:29,700 --> 00:32:33,740
So icons, their physical resemblance, correspondence,

641
00:32:33,740 --> 00:32:36,540
they don't tend to have much intentionality about them.

642
00:32:36,540 --> 00:32:39,660
A reflection in the water is there, whether you intended

643
00:32:39,660 --> 00:32:41,500
it to be there or not.

644
00:32:41,500 --> 00:32:44,260
But they can last after a reflection.

645
00:32:44,300 --> 00:32:47,420
But they can last after someone's not there.

646
00:32:47,420 --> 00:32:53,340
So the smell of a footprint can last for quite a while.

647
00:32:53,340 --> 00:32:56,820
All animals are able to interpret indexes.

648
00:32:56,820 --> 00:32:58,980
In fact, when we talk about animals'

649
00:32:58,980 --> 00:33:02,660
interpretation abilities, almost all the time in the

650
00:33:02,660 --> 00:33:05,180
experiments when they're talking about animals' learning

651
00:33:05,180 --> 00:33:07,660
symbols, in the Persian sense, they're not learning symbols.

652
00:33:07,660 --> 00:33:11,740
They're learning indexes and icons, which are very

653
00:33:11,740 --> 00:33:13,820
different levels of cognitive

654
00:33:13,820 --> 00:33:17,580
accomplishment from symbols.

655
00:33:17,580 --> 00:33:19,620
And so symbols are the final ones.

656
00:33:19,620 --> 00:33:21,460
And these are the properties that are important for us.

657
00:33:21,460 --> 00:33:22,780
No symbols, no language.

658
00:33:22,780 --> 00:33:24,420
They involve displacement.

659
00:33:24,420 --> 00:33:26,660
The thing that we're talking about doesn't actually have

660
00:33:26,660 --> 00:33:27,740
to be there.

661
00:33:27,740 --> 00:33:30,180
I can say water and hold this up, or I can say water

662
00:33:30,180 --> 00:33:30,820
without it there.

663
00:33:30,820 --> 00:33:32,460
And you still know what I'm talking about, that the

664
00:33:32,460 --> 00:33:35,460
object doesn't actually have to be there.

665
00:33:35,460 --> 00:33:36,900
Indexes last a long time.

666
00:33:36,900 --> 00:33:40,140
These footprints are about 3.7 million years old, found by

667
00:33:40,140 --> 00:33:44,820
Mary Leakey in, they're called the Laetoli footprints.

668
00:33:44,820 --> 00:33:47,820
And if you follow them out, you can see that it's a large

669
00:33:47,820 --> 00:33:51,660
Australopithesis probably, Australopithecus walking with

670
00:33:51,660 --> 00:33:53,780
a small one, and they walk, and they turn and look at

671
00:33:53,780 --> 00:33:55,980
something, and then they walk on.

672
00:33:55,980 --> 00:33:59,620
And it rained after they had walked by, and this is volcanic

673
00:33:59,620 --> 00:34:01,820
ash that hardened like concrete and left their

674
00:34:01,820 --> 00:34:03,620
footprints there.

675
00:34:03,620 --> 00:34:06,460
This is Australopithecus africanus.

676
00:34:06,460 --> 00:34:09,420
And as far as we can tell, they're the first creature to

677
00:34:09,420 --> 00:34:11,620
ever preserve an icon.

678
00:34:11,620 --> 00:34:16,980
So they're starting to look at things and contemplate, I

679
00:34:16,980 --> 00:34:18,460
don't think that's too strong a word,

680
00:34:18,460 --> 00:34:19,740
contemplate the similarities.

681
00:34:19,740 --> 00:34:23,740
So this stone, which is about 3 million years old, is called

682
00:34:23,740 --> 00:34:25,140
the Makapansgat pebble.

683
00:34:25,140 --> 00:34:28,860
It was found in a cave in South Africa, and it's unlike

684
00:34:28,860 --> 00:34:33,780
the material that the other stones in the cave were from.

685
00:34:33,780 --> 00:34:39,180
And if you look at it, it has an interesting characteristic.

686
00:34:39,180 --> 00:34:41,900
It looks like a smiley face.

687
00:34:41,900 --> 00:34:45,740
And this thing is about 3 inches by 2 inches, so it's too

688
00:34:45,740 --> 00:34:48,780
big to have gotten caught between their toes and carried

689
00:34:48,780 --> 00:34:50,900
up there coincidentally.

690
00:34:50,900 --> 00:34:53,540
This seems to be something that Australopithecus and

691
00:34:53,540 --> 00:34:56,420
Australopithecus found interesting and carried up to

692
00:34:56,420 --> 00:35:01,140
the cave with no particular functional role other than it

693
00:35:01,140 --> 00:35:04,100
looked like a face.

694
00:35:04,100 --> 00:35:07,300
Australopithecines also made tools.

695
00:35:07,340 --> 00:35:11,540
They're tools about 3.3 million years old, found in

696
00:35:11,540 --> 00:35:12,300
different places.

697
00:35:12,300 --> 00:35:17,340
They're the Oldowan tools discovered initially by the

698
00:35:17,340 --> 00:35:20,220
Leakey family.

699
00:35:20,220 --> 00:35:22,740
Icons are all over the place.

700
00:35:22,740 --> 00:35:26,180
In addition to seeing icons in nature, we have them in

701
00:35:26,180 --> 00:35:28,420
churches, and here are tools that have been actually made

702
00:35:28,420 --> 00:35:33,300
into icons and symbols, both.

703
00:35:33,300 --> 00:35:36,420
And from symbols to grammar, so how complex does a

704
00:35:36,420 --> 00:35:37,300
grammar have to be?

705
00:35:37,300 --> 00:35:40,340
Everybody will agree, every linguist will agree that you

706
00:35:40,340 --> 00:35:44,900
can't have a language until you have a grammar.

707
00:35:44,900 --> 00:35:47,220
But how complex does the grammar have to be?

708
00:35:47,220 --> 00:35:49,700
Well, there are a couple of different possibilities.

709
00:35:49,700 --> 00:35:53,500
And one of the points that I make in the book is that we

710
00:35:53,500 --> 00:35:55,860
find all of these in the world today.

711
00:35:55,860 --> 00:36:00,060
So one we could call a G1 grammar, which is just words

712
00:36:00,060 --> 00:36:02,220
put in a linear order.

713
00:36:02,260 --> 00:36:06,940
And that seems to be the case, for example, in Peta Ha and

714
00:36:06,940 --> 00:36:11,100
Riau, which is a language of New Guinea, which is

715
00:36:11,100 --> 00:36:13,060
John Saul Mary.

716
00:36:13,060 --> 00:36:15,100
So there's no other structure, let's say, in a

717
00:36:15,100 --> 00:36:15,820
language like this.

718
00:36:15,820 --> 00:36:20,140
There's just those three words, John Saul Mary.

719
00:36:20,140 --> 00:36:25,500
A G2 grammar would be like a G1 grammar, but have additional

720
00:36:25,500 --> 00:36:27,620
hierarchy or structure into the phrases.

721
00:36:27,620 --> 00:36:34,140
So the man you saw yesterday is here, where you saw

722
00:36:34,140 --> 00:36:40,180
yesterday as a sentence hierarchically located inside

723
00:36:40,180 --> 00:36:44,940
a larger sentence, or you could simply say the very big

724
00:36:44,940 --> 00:36:47,220
ball rolled down the hill.

725
00:36:47,220 --> 00:36:48,860
There you start to get more structure.

726
00:36:48,860 --> 00:36:51,660
It's not simply linear order of words.

727
00:36:51,660 --> 00:36:54,980
A G3 grammar has both recursion and hierarchy.

728
00:36:54,980 --> 00:36:56,300
So what is recursion?

729
00:36:56,300 --> 00:36:59,260
It's the ability to put one thing inside another of the

730
00:36:59,260 --> 00:37:01,020
same type and just keep doing it.

731
00:37:01,020 --> 00:37:08,340
So the man who is here said that Bill said that Mary said

732
00:37:08,340 --> 00:37:12,180
that Peter said that John bought a house.

733
00:37:12,180 --> 00:37:14,180
When you start to get structures like that so that

734
00:37:14,180 --> 00:37:17,340
you can say there's no longer a sentence in a language, then

735
00:37:17,340 --> 00:37:19,140
recursion is the best way to handle that.

736
00:37:19,140 --> 00:37:22,180
And recursion is communicatively very useful.

737
00:37:22,180 --> 00:37:24,260
You can pack a lot more information in a

738
00:37:24,260 --> 00:37:27,340
sentence with recursion.

739
00:37:27,340 --> 00:37:30,740
But I've argued that although recursion can be found in any

740
00:37:30,740 --> 00:37:33,980
language, it's not a necessary component of all languages.

741
00:37:33,980 --> 00:37:36,140
And in fact, there are good reasons why some

742
00:37:36,140 --> 00:37:37,500
languages would avoid it.

743
00:37:39,940 --> 00:37:41,820
So erectus had icons.

744
00:37:41,820 --> 00:37:43,500
We know that they carry things around.

745
00:37:43,500 --> 00:37:46,940
They didn't carry around smiley faces that we know of, but

746
00:37:46,940 --> 00:37:51,300
they did carry around phallic symbols like this cuttlefish

747
00:37:51,300 --> 00:37:57,620
bone that was found in Morocco about 450,000 years ago.

748
00:37:57,620 --> 00:38:02,980
And erectus also started making quite complex tools.

749
00:38:02,980 --> 00:38:07,460
So there are three grades of tools in the paleolithic,

750
00:38:07,460 --> 00:38:09,460
especially in the lower paleolithic.

751
00:38:09,460 --> 00:38:11,940
There are oldivon tools about 3 million years ago.

752
00:38:11,940 --> 00:38:16,020
There are achulian tools made as recently as 200,000 years

753
00:38:16,020 --> 00:38:16,820
ago.

754
00:38:16,820 --> 00:38:19,980
And then finally, there are levelwa tools, which are the

755
00:38:19,980 --> 00:38:24,060
most complex tools found in the paleolithic.

756
00:38:24,060 --> 00:38:27,180
So these are refined, which means they've been thinned.

757
00:38:27,180 --> 00:38:32,140
These take quite a bit of effort and skill to function.

758
00:38:32,140 --> 00:38:34,700
And they have various parts to them.

759
00:38:34,700 --> 00:38:37,580
You don't just start off banging two rocks together to

760
00:38:37,580 --> 00:38:38,260
get one of those.

761
00:38:38,260 --> 00:38:39,780
You have to have a plan.

762
00:38:39,780 --> 00:38:42,620
There are certain things that have to be cut out of the tool.

763
00:38:42,620 --> 00:38:47,100
It has to have a certain shape to be functional.

764
00:38:47,100 --> 00:38:49,220
So when erectus started working on tools, they might

765
00:38:49,260 --> 00:38:50,700
start with a large piece of rock.

766
00:38:50,700 --> 00:38:53,900
And out of that, they had to break out the pieces that

767
00:38:53,900 --> 00:38:57,220
they needed to get the kind of functional tool.

768
00:38:57,220 --> 00:39:02,780
And they make them all pretty much the same to work for them.

769
00:39:02,780 --> 00:39:05,140
Erectus was the first to come up with a controlled use of

770
00:39:05,140 --> 00:39:06,140
fire.

771
00:39:06,140 --> 00:39:09,540
The pre-shaping of stone tools, working them before they

772
00:39:09,540 --> 00:39:12,980
actually started chiseling out the tools, they used wood and

773
00:39:12,980 --> 00:39:14,580
bone tools as well.

774
00:39:14,580 --> 00:39:17,180
And we think they might have also used hafted tools.

775
00:39:17,180 --> 00:39:19,820
And hafted tools are quite important because that's when

776
00:39:19,820 --> 00:39:23,140
you tie a handle on that shows a lot of functional

