00:39:54,340 --> 00:39:59,380
that that's not simply a functional aspect of toolmaking.

786
00:39:59,380 --> 00:40:04,340
That is an aspect of toolmaking that shows thought

787
00:40:04,340 --> 00:40:07,140
that goes above the mere function of the tool.

788
00:40:07,140 --> 00:40:10,780
Hafting tools, combinatorial thinking, imagining the

789
00:40:10,780 --> 00:40:14,660
future, and likely invented by erectus.

790
00:40:14,660 --> 00:40:16,620
It's one of the most significant technological

791
00:40:16,620 --> 00:40:20,220
breakthroughs in human toolmaking.

792
00:40:20,220 --> 00:40:23,340
And ochre is also very important.

793
00:40:23,340 --> 00:40:26,420
And we see things like hand axes.

794
00:40:26,420 --> 00:40:29,980
They had a tool kit, not nearly as extensive as an

795
00:40:29,980 --> 00:40:33,260
Neanderthal tool kit or as a Homo sapiens tool kit, but as

796
00:40:33,260 --> 00:40:35,820
an extensive tool kit.

797
00:40:35,820 --> 00:40:37,700
They had hand axes and cleavers.

798
00:40:37,700 --> 00:40:39,540
They had picks.

799
00:40:39,580 --> 00:40:41,180
And so we see different stages.

800
00:40:41,180 --> 00:40:43,980
We should recall the simple stage of Oldowan tools that we

801
00:40:43,980 --> 00:40:47,860
saw that Australopithecus had.

802
00:40:47,860 --> 00:40:49,500
We see achulian tools.

803
00:40:49,500 --> 00:40:52,060
These are already starting to get refined and showing a lot

804
00:40:52,060 --> 00:40:53,340
more work.

805
00:40:53,340 --> 00:40:57,860
And then we get to the Cadillac of the tools of

806
00:40:57,860 --> 00:41:01,420
erectus-level-wa tools.

807
00:41:01,420 --> 00:41:04,220
Not everyone agrees that erectus-made-level-wa tools.

